\subsection{A Brief Review of Three Modern Geometrical Theory of Diffraction}\label{LR_Three_GTD}\index{GTD}
These are high frequency asymptotic techniques. They were developed as direct solutions to practical (radiation and scattering) boundary value problems for Maxwell\rq s equations. The basic assumption in all these techniques is that at high frequency, that is as $k\rightarrow\infty$ (k=wave number), diffraction is a locally determined phenomenon. This implies that the diffracted field is determined by the local properties of the incidence field and the diffracting obstacle at the point of diffraction. Based on this assumption is the idea of \lq canonical\rq~problems that are simpler problems having the same local features as the problems under consideration and possible having an exact solution. These techniques have been based on the asymptotic expansion of the exact solution to certain canonical problems. When applied to more complex situations they give asymptotic solutions that are in general approximate.

All these theories have in common individual \lq Ansatz\rq~based on Sommerfeld\rq s classic solution to the problem of plane wave diffraction by a half-plane \cite{Sommerfeld_Math_Theorie_Diffraktion}, \cite{Boersma_a_simple_solution_of_Sommerfelds_half_plane_diffraction_problem}.



\subsubsection{Sommerfeld\rq s Solution}\label{LR_Sommerfeld_Solution}\index{Sommerfeld\rq s solution}
Consider a plane wave $u^i\left(r,\phi\right)$ incident at an angle $\phi'$ on an infinitely conducting half-plane at $x\le,~y=0$ (Fig.~\ref{Fig:plane_wave_diff_half_plne_1}). The incident field is decomposed into E-polarized and H-polarized parts. The total field obtained by Sommerfeld is of the form:
\begin{align}\label{ltsr_Sommerfeld_eq}
u^t\left(r,\phi\right)=U\left(r,\phi\right)+R~U\left(r,4\pi-\phi\right)
\end{align}
Here $R=-1 (+1)$, when the incident field has E-field (H-field) parallel to the edge at $x=0,~y=0$. The wave function $U\left(r,\phi\right)$ is double valued and of period $4\pi$. The first term $U\left(r,\phi\right)$ in (\ref{ltsr_Sommerfeld_eq}) is the contribution due to the incident wave, while the second term $U\left(r,4\pi-\phi\right)$ is that of the reflected wave.
